article.headline: Towson 74, Northeastern 61
article.story: TOWSON, Md. (AP) -- Dennard Abraham had 16 points and seven rebounds, C.C. Williams added a career-high 15 points and Towson beat Northeastern 74-61 Wednesday night. The Tigers (12-11, 6-6 Colonial Athletic Association) placed five players in double figures in matching their win total from last season. Gary Neal scored 11 points and Tommy Breaux and Jonathan Pease had 10 apiece for Towson, which has won five of seven. Matt Janning led the Huskies (7-16, 5-7) with 18 points. Eugene Spates had 15 points and seven rebounds and Bennet Davis 12 points for Northeastern, which has lost two straight and fell to 0-13 on the road. Towson overcame a rough night by Neal, who was averaging 25.7 points a game but played on a gimpy ankle. Though he finished 4-for-15 from the floor and 0-for-7 from 3-point range, Neal still dished out eight assists. Breaux slammed an alley-OOP lob from Williams, starting a game-opening 9-0 run by Towson. Northeastern didn't convert from the field until Davis' jump-hook after 4:27 had elapsed and Abraham scored 11 first-half points to help the Tigers to a 40-27 lead at halftime. A 9-0 run early in the second half helped the Huskies cut the lead to 43-36, but Williams scored consecutive transition baskets for an 11-point cushion. Janning hit two 3-pointers during a 12-2 Northeastern burst that trimmed the deficit to 58-51 before Williams' 10-foot jumper ignited a 10-0 Towson run, capped by a Tim Crossin 3-pointer with 3:59 remaining.
